<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18390617-1997">
               <interp inst="t18390617-1997" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18390617"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18390617-1997" type="date" value="18390617"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18390617-1997-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1997-18390617 t18390617-1997-offence-1 t18390617-1997-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1997. <persName id="def1-1997-18390617" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1997-18390617" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1997-18390617" type="age" value="19"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1997-18390617" type="surname" value="MARKS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1997-18390617" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM MARKS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18390617-1997-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390617-1997-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390617-1997-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18390617-cd-242" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390617-1997-offence-1 t18390617-cd-242"></join>4th of May</rs>, 3500 lbs. weight of iron, value 10., the goods of <persName id="t18390617-name-1541" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1541" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1541" type="surname" value="PLUMLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1541" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1541" type="occupation" value="owns an iron-yard"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390617-1997-offence-1 t18390617-name-1541"></join>Peter Plumley</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1542" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1542" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1542" type="surname" value="HARLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1542" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>FRANCIS HARLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Peter Plumley—he is in possession of an iron-yard, where he carries on business, in Broadway, Southwark—on the 4th of May the prisoner was in his employ, and likewise Bennett and Barrett—I had twenty tons of iron to deliver at a wharf—the pri<lb></lb>soner is a carman, and so is Bennett—each of them drove a cart on this occasion—Barrett was sent down to the wharf to see that all the iron was</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183906170288"></xptr>
               <p>put into the vessel, and to assist in putting it in—I sent down seven loads before any thing happened—when the seventh had got there the captain discovered something—I was called on by the captain about one o'clock—I asked the prisoner if he had taken away one of these loads, and he denied it—I was by when Hogarth asked him what he had done with the load which he had shot under the archway—he said he had not shot it, but <hi rend="italic">Jack</hi> Barrett had—the wharf is about half a mile from the Broad<lb></lb>way—it is called Mark Brown's Wharf—the arch is in the railway, near Crucifix-lane—that is out of the road to the wharf—they had no authority whatever to take the goods any where hut from the Broadway to the wharf—I was at the station-house where the prisoner was taken—he asked me if I had been to the King and Queen, at Rotherhithe, for the iron—I made no answer—I had not been there—I have been there since, and found some iron—it appeared to me in all respects similar to what we had lost.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long has the prisoner been in your master's employ? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Ever since the winter—the load on each cart was about 30cwts.—the prisoner went home after I questioned him, and returned again—he went out with two or three loads in the morning, and one or two in the afternoon—Barrett has been in my master's service a long time—he is older than the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1543" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1543" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1543" type="surname" value="HOGARTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1543" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HOGARTH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Plumley. On the 4th of May I asked the prisoner what he had done with one of the loads of iron, which I understood he had placed under the Greenwich railway—he admitted it had been shot there, but said he had not shot it—I said I thought he had, and ordered one of the men to go immediately for a policeman—I went with the officer up to the arch—the prisoner said that was the arch where the iron had been shot, and I saw the dust of old iron on the ground.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did he say who did shoot it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was very angry, I do not remember whether he did or not—I do not remember hearing any thing pass between him and Harley—I gave him in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1544" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1544" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1544" type="surname" value="HIGGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1544" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HIGGS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 92.) I was sent for, and took the prisoner for stealing 31 cwts. of iron, on Saturday the 4th of May—Mr. Hogarth wished me to take him under the railway arch where the iron had been shot—we went there—it was one of the arches near Crucifix-lane—the prisoner said he was in a public-house drinking a pint of beer, and some one drove away the horse and cart—he did not know who it was—he said he did not know what public-house it was, but it was in Tooley-street, and he found the horse and cart under the railway arch, the iron shot there, and no one was with it—while at the station-house he sat down, and said he had been led astray by <hi rend="italic">Jack</hi> Barrett; that <hi rend="italic">Jack</hi> Barrett had come to him in Tooley-street, and they both drove the horse and cart down Dog and Bear yard, and shot the iron under the railway arch, near Cruci<lb></lb>fix-lane; That Jack Barrett was to look after the iron—he said that jack Barrett and him were colleagued together in stealing the iron, they were Going to sell it, and part the money between them; and if I would let Him go that afternoon, he would go to the King and Queen iron-foundry, Where he should find the iron and the parties.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Are you sure he said <hi rend="italic">Jack</hi> Barrett was to look after the iron? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—and he was to go home—I did not tell him what he was to go to the station-house for—Mr. Hogarth had told him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1545" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1545" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1545" type="surname" value="DUNN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1545" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH DUNN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Church-street, St. John's, and keep horses</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183906170289"></xptr>
               <p>and carts for hire. On Saturday morning, the 4th of May, between eleven and twelve o'clock, I was standing near Cotton's wharf, in Tooley-street—<hi rend="italic">Jack</hi> Barrett came to another man, and was engaging with him to do a job for him—I touched him twice over the back with my whip, and he turned round, and said—"Ah <hi rend="italic">Joe</hi> I have got a job for you"—he took me to Dog and Bear-yard, and there was some old iron shot under the arch of the rail-road, but How it came there I do not know—it was put into my cart—I drove it to the King and Queen, where he told me—he was with me, and gave me 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—he had 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. on account of it—I saw it in his hand.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> The prisoner was not with you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1546" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1546" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1546" type="surname" value="DYER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1546" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH DYER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Messrs. Howard and Co., proprietors of the King and Queen iron works, Rotherhithe. On the 4th of May Joseph Dunn and another man, who I understand was Barrett, came to my master's premises with a load of iron—I gave him 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for it—it was worth about 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—we should have weighed it on the following Monday, and paid him the remainder—from 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. per ton—we knew nothing of him, but we buy iron if it is of the usual description, and nothing suspicions about it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had you seen Barrett before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot say that I had—I might have seen him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Hurley afterwards see the iron? and Mr. Hogarth saw it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18390617-1997-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-1997-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-1997-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 19.—
<rs id="t18390617-1997-punishment-239" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390617-1997-punishment-239" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390617-1997-punishment-239" type="punishmentSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1997-18390617 t18390617-1997-punishment-239"></join>Confined Six Months</rs>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Before Mr. Sergeant Arabin.</hi>
               </p>
